Document: DirectionalLight2D  
Path: godot/classes/class_directionallight2d.rst  
Summary: A directional light node emitting parallel rays from a distant source, used for effects like sunlight or moonlight.  

A directional light is a type of Light2D node that models an infinite number of parallel rays covering the entire scene. It is used for lights with strong intensity located far away from the scene (e.g., sunlight or moonlight). Light is emitted in the +Y direction of the node's global basis. For an unrotated light, this means the light is emitted downwards. The position of the node is ignored; only the basis is used to determine light direction.  

Note: DirectionalLight2D does not support light cull masks (but supports shadow cull masks) and will always light 2D nodes regardless of their CanvasItem.light_mask property. Inherits: Light2D.
